00:12:52,140 --> 00:12:57,140
And that seems like, yeah, we are making trade offs, but there might be room to solve those.

241
00:12:57,140 --> 00:13:04,320
Whereas there are some places where like if you're so far out of town that you can't go anywhere and get any decent food in the evening, then you can't really solve that as easily.

242
00:13:04,320 --> 00:13:09,060
I did think that Belfast shuts down more over the Easter weekend than a lot of places we've been.

243
00:13:09,060 --> 00:13:13,800
There are a lot more places that seem to close very early on Sundays or were kind of closed on the bank holiday.

244
00:13:13,800 --> 00:13:18,480
It is a long time since we've been to Liverpool for an Easter con.

245
00:13:18,480 --> 00:13:28,220
But one of the things about Liverpool for the Easter con was that we would spend some energy in trying to persuade local bars and restaurants to stay open.

246
00:13:28,220 --> 00:13:31,840
I mean, before the weekend, we would go in and say, we are doing this.

247
00:13:31,840 --> 00:13:33,080
People will want to eat.

248
00:13:33,080 --> 00:13:39,120
If you are open on Good Friday and Easter Monday and Easter Sunday, then things will be better for you.

249
00:13:39,120 --> 00:13:40,380
I think things have changed a bit.

250
00:13:40,500 --> 00:13:45,920
People say Belfast is a lot more open over the weekend than it was 10 or 20 years ago.

251
00:13:45,920 --> 00:13:47,140
And I well believe that.

252
00:13:47,140 --> 00:13:53,100
Well, when we were sort of discussing in committee, one of the committee members was like, remember, everything will be shut on Sunday.

253
00:13:53,100 --> 00:13:54,080
It will be a nightmare.

254
00:13:54,080 --> 00:13:57,840
And then I went out and ate and drank on Sunday.

255
00:13:57,840 --> 00:14:01,700
And I was like, this seems to be a very pleasant nightmare, which I'm quite enjoying, really.

256
00:14:01,700 --> 00:14:04,340
And so I think you're probably right.

257
00:14:04,340 --> 00:14:11,980
I think my impression and especially my impression from talking to people in Belfast is that it's changed quite a lot since Covid.

258
00:14:11,980 --> 00:14:21,900
And I wonder whether the shock of everything forcibly going away for a while made the restaurants think, well, if we open on Sundays, we'd get we might be able to get some more money and that might be quite helpful.

259
00:14:21,900 --> 00:14:24,980
And then other people are like, oh, going out on Sundays is quite nice, isn't it?

260
00:14:24,980 --> 00:14:28,800
I believe Belfast City Council also changed some.

261
00:14:28,800 --> 00:14:30,640
Possibly, possibly some rules.

262
00:14:30,640 --> 00:14:34,360
They made it they definitely made it easier for people to open over the Easter weekend.

263
00:14:34,360 --> 00:14:35,880
Well, that's the other thing.

264
00:14:35,880 --> 00:14:43,960
Having been in Vienna a week later on a on May Day on May Day, supermarkets don't open in Austria.

265
00:14:43,960 --> 00:14:46,260
And on Sundays, supermarkets don't open in Austria.

266
00:14:46,260 --> 00:14:51,740
So like Belfast is very open compared to some places in Europe.

267
00:14:51,740 --> 00:14:53,780
So Ali also talks about social hubs.

268
00:14:53,780 --> 00:14:55,020
What were our thoughts on that?

269
00:14:55,020 --> 00:15:07,280
I was quite surprised to see this because and I understand that I like bars, but I thought that the Hilton bar was placed almost exactly equidistant from both chunks of programme space.

270
00:15:07,280 --> 00:15:09,800
So it was, in fact, a central location.

271
00:15:09,800 --> 00:15:17,300
And you could either walk one way through to the conference centre or the other way up to the Hilton's programme spaces.

272
00:15:18,180 --> 00:15:20,820
And it kind of seemed fine to me.

273
00:15:20,820 --> 00:15:22,140
And I spent quite a lot of time there.

274
00:15:22,140 --> 00:15:25,900
Maybe not quite as much as I like because some of the time it was a bit kind of noisy and full.

275
00:15:25,900 --> 00:15:29,180
But most of the time it was great as a central space.

276
00:15:29,180 --> 00:15:37,260
There was also kind of there were kind of rather impersonal lobbies for both of the for both of the sets of conference space.

277
00:15:37,260 --> 00:15:39,620
But I'm not sure either of those are really great hangout spaces.

278
00:15:39,620 --> 00:15:43,000
They were good places to sort of rest for a little while between items.

279
00:15:43,640 --> 00:15:47,420
So I think, yeah, I agree with Alison in part.

280
00:15:47,420 --> 00:15:53,020
I don't think the space was quite equidistant from the two sides of the convention because I think it probably was closer to the Hilton than the ICC.

281
00:15:53,020 --> 00:15:54,920
But it was relatively marginal.

282
00:15:54,920 --> 00:15:59,680
And I think in general it had quite a good central space for that.

283
00:15:59,680 --> 00:16:07,800
But I will also say I'm not sure I'm I've never been a huge fan of conventions that only have one obvious social area.

284
00:16:08,380 --> 00:16:13,480
I quite like having a mixture of places to hang out and catch up with people.

285
00:16:13,480 --> 00:16:24,120
Yeah, I think it felt like the Hilton social space was good, but it was probably a bit far from the convention center to be the obvious social space if you wanted to hang out there.

286
00:16:24,120 --> 00:16:28,440
And the convention center social spaces were a bit not.

287
00:16:28,440 --> 00:16:31,120
They're a bit sort of sterile and convention centery.

288
00:16:31,120 --> 00:16:37,960
There was only that really that one area outside the art show that it had sort of tables and chairs could hang out in.

289
00:16:37,960 --> 00:16:40,360
Then there were some other kind of scattered sofas, which I did like.

290
00:16:40,620 --> 00:16:47,820
But then downstairs at registration where there were some, you know, there were some kind of displays and stuff on.

291
00:16:47,820 --> 00:16:49,780
I think Blood on the Clock Tower was played down there.

292
00:16:49,780 --> 00:16:54,500
It's a shame there wasn't a bit more sort of like social space hangouty stuff that you could do down there.

293
00:16:54,500 --> 00:16:59,920
I think that's obviously going to be a problem with any site that's a convention center hotel split.

294
00:17:00,460 --> 00:17:06,780
But in general, I thought the ICC Hilton worked really well as a convention site.

295
00:17:06,780 --> 00:17:14,220
Obviously, I suspect if stairs are a problem for you as an access thing, then having to get the lift from one to the other was probably a bit of a pain in the neck.

296
00:17:14,220 --> 00:17:17,460
But I don't know if anyone listening has opinions on that.

297
00:17:17,460 --> 00:17:19,520
Please do write in because I'd be interested to learn.

298
00:17:19,520 --> 00:17:23,260
Well, I have some opinions on this because I use the lifts all weekend.

299
00:17:23,260 --> 00:17:23,840
Oh.

300
00:17:23,840 --> 00:17:30,420
Which is, I think, the first time at an Easter con I've really felt, oh, yeah, that's going to make it a lot easier for me.

301
00:17:30,420 --> 00:17:32,180
And they were fine.

302
00:17:32,180 --> 00:17:39,800
And that's maybe why I think it's a bit more equidistant because there was just one little lift to get down to the conference center or up.

303
00:17:39,800 --> 00:17:40,540
I'm not quite sure.

304
00:17:40,540 --> 00:17:45,000
There was one lift that took you one floor to get from the Hilton to the conference center.

305
00:17:45,000 --> 00:17:46,620
That was normally empty.

306
00:17:46,620 --> 00:17:49,860
And there was the main Hilton lifts.

307
00:17:49,860 --> 00:17:53,060
There was normally a not very long queue for.

308
00:17:53,060 --> 00:17:54,540
So it was fine.

309
00:17:54,540 --> 00:17:58,200
But they were quite slow because as well as serving the mezzanine.

310
00:17:58,200 --> 00:18:05,560
I mean, that felt like a hotel that really needed escalators up to the mezzanine, which would certainly have it, but was built now or made in America.

311
00:18:05,560 --> 00:18:07,660
Yeah.

312
00:18:07,660 --> 00:18:09,700
Rather than that big staircase in the lobby.

313
00:18:09,700 --> 00:18:12,020
So you were reliant on the Hilton lifts.

314
00:18:12,020 --> 00:18:19,580
And they were kind of if you were trying to get up to a program item at a point when there were like a lot of people going back and forth to their rooms.

315
00:18:19,580 --> 00:18:20,940
It could take quite a long time.

316
00:18:20,940 --> 00:18:33,300
Nowadays, hotels like that are built with escalators up to the mezzanine and then lifts that will take you to the bedroom floors because of this exact problem, especially if they've got a lot of conference space.

317
00:18:33,300 --> 00:18:37,560
But if they had escalators, then you couldn't use the stairs for photo shoots.

318
00:18:39,240 --> 00:18:40,740
As I did see one day.

319
00:18:40,740 --> 00:18:41,900
Okay.

320
00:18:41,900 --> 00:18:50,640
I mean, you know, I kind of think of both stairs and escalators have been primarily to move people around a building rather than to provide Instagram backdrops.

321
00:18:50,640 --> 00:18:51,760
But what do I know?

322
00:18:51,760 --> 00:19:00,340
Oh, the other thing I know, the other thing I wanted to say about the layout, which is in general, it was all fine, except there were program rooms called the boardroom.

323
00:19:00,340 --> 00:19:05,480
In both the Hilton and the conference center and nothing was done to distinguish these.

324
00:19:05,480 --> 00:19:11,700
So I turned up for at least one program item in the wrong one and went, oh, no.

325
00:19:11,700 --> 00:19:15,340
And of course, by the time I got over to the other one, which took quite a long time, it was full.

326
00:19:15,340 --> 00:19:16,360
So, boo.

327
00:19:16,360 --> 00:19:17,000
Yeah.

328
00:19:17,000 --> 00:19:20,460
So I thought the convention would quite well from a flow perspective.

329
00:19:20,460 --> 00:19:22,800
So, yeah, it was nice to look around.

330
00:19:22,800 --> 00:19:23,700
Look around?

331
00:19:23,700 --> 00:19:24,920
Nice to walk around.

332
00:19:25,080 --> 00:19:30,660
I also really liked that the art show and the fan tables were next to each other and there was like a place you could hang out there.

333
00:19:30,660 --> 00:19:32,060
I think that felt very good.

334
00:19:32,060 --> 00:19:36,240
And I think part of the problem here is that, like, it's tricky, right?

335
00:19:36,240 --> 00:19:39,820
Because on this podcast, we do a lot of critiquing conventions.

336
00:19:39,820 --> 00:19:43,060
And I think it's good and wise to critique conventions.

337
00:19:43,060 --> 00:19:50,700
